1
00:00:01,693 --> 00:00:03,127
<i>Previously on</i> Fringe...

2
00:00:03,796 --> 00:00:07,048
I crossed into another universe
and took a son that wasn't mine.

3
00:00:07,696 --> 00:00:10,903
Not a day has passed
without me feeling the burden

4
00:00:11,028 --> 00:00:11,982
of that act.

5
00:00:12,107 --> 00:00:14,221
Peter deserves to know the truth
about who he is.

6
00:00:14,389 --> 00:00:17,099
You saved his life.
I am sure that he will understand.

7
00:00:17,579 --> 00:00:19,949
You didn't just open up a hole
to the other side.

8
00:00:20,604 --> 00:00:22,396
- You brought me back.
- Son, this...

9
00:00:22,564 --> 00:00:24,357
I am not your son.

10
00:00:25,968 --> 00:00:28,194
Peter checked himself out
of the hospital three hours ago.

11
00:00:28,619 --> 00:00:29,619
He's gone.

12
00:01:28,202 --> 00:01:30,535
I've decided that we need
to get organized.

13
00:01:30,660 --> 00:01:32,174
You've been smoking marijuana.

14
00:01:32,342 --> 00:01:35,720
I'd hardly classify
what I've just smoked as marijuana.

15
00:01:36,423 --> 00:01:37,638
It's a hybrid

16
00:01:37,806 --> 00:01:41,436
of chronic supernova
and afghani kush.

17
00:01:43,792 --> 00:01:45,493
I call it Brown Betty.

18
00:01:55,944 --> 00:01:57,429
I know how you're feeling.

19
00:01:59,944 --> 00:02:02,744
It's important to take
control of one's life.

20
00:02:04,156 --> 00:02:06,459
Peter is going to come back.

21
00:02:07,495 --> 00:02:09,195
He just needs some time.

22
00:02:10,571 --> 00:02:12,310
But he will come back.

23
00:02:22,380 --> 00:02:24,188
Is there news?
Have you found him?

24
00:02:25,419 --> 00:02:26,646
I'm sorry, Walter.

25
00:02:26,964 --> 00:02:29,690
I have some leads that I would like
to follow up, but I have to...

26
00:02:29,858 --> 00:02:30,910
You have to what?

27
00:02:31,542 --> 00:02:33,573
What can be more important
than finding Peter?

28
00:02:33,698 --> 00:02:36,572
Aunt Liv. The snack machine stole
the dollar you gave me.

29
00:02:37,746 --> 00:02:40,926
- Hi, Astrid. Hi, uncle Walter.
- Hi, Ella.

30
00:02:41,349 --> 00:02:44,701
You know what? We have some snacks
back there in the fridge.

31
00:02:44,826 --> 00:02:46,753
- You can go help yourself.
- Thanks.

32
00:02:48,945 --> 00:02:49,995
Who's that?

33
00:02:51,873 --> 00:02:54,173
- It smells funny in here.
- Rachel's daughter.

34
00:02:54,341 --> 00:02:55,883
Rachel's Olivia's sister.

35
00:02:56,167 --> 00:02:58,734
Rachel had to go to Chicago
for the weekend, so...

36
00:02:58,859 --> 00:03:00,596
she asked
if I could look after Ella.

37
00:03:00,764 --> 00:03:03,061
I was wondering
if maybe you could watch her...

38
00:03:04,168 --> 00:03:06,418
I couldn't possibly
look after anyone else.

39
00:03:06,543 --> 00:03:09,629
- I'm well into phase one.
- I think she's talking about me.

40
00:03:10,645 --> 00:03:12,691
Walter just smoked something
called "Brown Betty."

41
00:03:13,658 --> 00:03:15,694
- Hi, cow.
- Be careful, Stella.

42
00:03:16,191 --> 00:03:18,556
Gene, Gene, no licking.
No licking.

43
00:03:19,762 --> 00:03:22,152
You should only have
to watch her for a few hours.

44
00:03:22,277 --> 00:03:26,038
Don't worry, Olivia. I will be here.
We would love to have her.

45
00:03:27,365 --> 00:03:30,042
You're killing him.
You're not supposed to touch the sides.

46
00:03:30,463 --> 00:03:32,177
What kind of doctor are you?

47
00:03:32,302 --> 00:03:33,689
You're not even trying.

48
00:03:34,467 --> 00:03:35,517
His heart.

49
00:03:35,859 --> 00:03:39,009
All you've done is eat all my snacks
and talk about weird stuff.

50
00:03:39,404 --> 00:03:40,803
And everything makes you laugh.

51
00:03:42,627 --> 00:03:44,682
I know!
Why don't you tell me a story?

52
00:03:45,128 --> 00:03:48,310
- I'm not very good at stories.
- Didn't you used to tell stories?

53
00:03:51,691 --> 00:03:53,524
I'm sure Mrs. Bishop did, but...

54
00:03:54,959 --> 00:03:57,143
No, I never told Peter stories.

55
00:03:58,438 --> 00:03:59,688
I was always...

56
00:04:00,371 --> 00:04:02,491
too busy with my work.

57
00:04:04,154 --> 00:04:07,496
What about your parents, uncle Walter?
Didn't they tell you stories?

58
00:04:10,597 --> 00:04:12,139
My mother...

59
00:04:13,069 --> 00:04:14,667
loved Chandler

60
00:04:14,792 --> 00:04:17,464
and another writer
called Dashiell Hammett.

61
00:04:18,083 --> 00:04:20,305
She loved detective stories.

62
00:04:21,449 --> 00:04:24,638
And musicals!
She adored musicals!

63
00:04:25,351 --> 00:04:29,268
She often would dress me up
to play parts in plays at school.

64
00:04:29,627 --> 00:04:32,109
I was roughed up
quite a lot as a child.

65
00:04:32,974 --> 00:04:36,233
Walter, I think that Ella would
really enjoy a story.

66
00:04:37,037 --> 00:04:38,387
Once upon a time.

67
00:04:39,347 --> 00:04:41,363
Well, all right. Are you ready?

68
00:04:44,983 --> 00:04:47,602
Once upon a time...

69
00:04:50,832 --> 00:04:53,626
there was an accomplished detective.

70
00:04:55,670 --> 00:04:58,865
Except that she had
decided to retire,

71
00:04:59,515 --> 00:05:00,549
pack it in,

72
00:05:00,717 --> 00:05:04,706
because there was one mystery
she could not solve.

73
00:05:04,831 --> 00:05:05,867
What was that?

74
00:05:05,992 --> 00:05:08,508
How to mend a broken heart.

75
00:05:16,315 --> 00:05:19,124
My name is Rachel.
I'm sorry to just show up like this,

76
00:05:19,249 --> 00:05:22,321
but I have left you several messages,
and I'd like to hire you.

77
00:05:22,722 --> 00:05:24,437
My boyfriend, he's gone missing.

78
00:05:26,046 --> 00:05:27,670
As you can see, I'm kinda busy.

79
00:05:27,795 --> 00:05:29,626
He got in over his head
to a gambler.

80
00:05:29,751 --> 00:05:32,915
A guy named Big Eddie. I'm afraid
something bad may have happened to him.

81
00:05:33,083 --> 00:05:33,958
Drown him?

82
00:05:34,126 --> 00:05:35,223
I'm sorry, what?

83
00:05:37,129 --> 00:05:38,083
No, thank you.

84
00:05:40,414 --> 00:05:42,648
You know, most times
when someone comes in here

85
00:05:42,773 --> 00:05:45,226
worried that their sweetheart's
gone missing, or worse...

86
00:05:45,761 --> 00:05:48,169
By the time they find out
what I usually find out,

87
00:05:48,718 --> 00:05:50,766
they wind up wishing
he really were dead.

88
00:05:51,214 --> 00:05:52,977
What do you usually find out?

89
00:05:53,882 --> 00:05:54,853
Rachel, is it?

90
00:05:56,251 --> 00:05:57,751
Do yourself a favor.

91
00:05:58,633 --> 00:05:59,636
Go home.

92
00:06:00,094 --> 00:06:02,466
He wouldn't do
what you're suggesting.

93
00:06:03,494 --> 00:06:05,688
We met only a few weeks ago, but...

94
00:06:06,536 --> 00:06:07,908
it was love at first sight.

95
00:06:10,384 --> 00:06:13,619
You probably don't believe
something like that exists.

96
00:06:13,744 --> 00:06:16,503
But I assure you it does.

97
00:06:17,966 --> 00:06:21,807
<i>Something happens
and I'm head over heels</i>

98
00:06:21,932 --> 00:06:26,927
<i>I never find out
till I'm head over heels</i>

99
00:06:27,776 --> 00:06:31,642
<i>Something happens
and I'm head over heels</i>

100
00:06:32,563 --> 00:06:34,905
<i>Don't take my heart,
don't break my heart</i>

101
00:06:35,030 --> 00:06:37,829
<i>Don't, don't,
don't throw it away</i>

102
00:06:41,560 --> 00:06:43,860
What those school kids
must've done to you.

103
00:06:44,333 --> 00:06:46,337
Maybe you should teach me algebra.

104
00:06:48,140 --> 00:06:49,230
You see, the...

105
00:06:50,763 --> 00:06:53,246
the medication
that uncle Walter is on,

106
00:06:53,371 --> 00:06:55,642
causes his posterior

107
00:06:55,767 --> 00:06:59,141
and lateral cricoarytenoid muscles

108
00:07:00,024 --> 00:07:01,670
to contract his larynx's.

109
00:07:05,501 --> 00:07:07,134
Anyway, what was I saying?

110
00:07:09,750 --> 00:07:10,750
True love.

111
00:07:15,972 --> 00:07:17,818
When was the last time
you spoke to him?

112
00:07:19,073 --> 00:07:20,981
On the telephone two days ago.

113
00:07:21,285 --> 00:07:22,632
Okay, and what's his name?

114
00:07:28,315 --> 00:07:30,077
Wait a minute. That's wrong.

115
00:07:30,419 --> 00:07:32,910
- My mom doesn't love Peter.
- Of course not.

116
00:07:33,242 --> 00:07:34,526
It's just a story.

117
00:07:35,325 --> 00:07:36,212
But,

118
00:07:36,337 --> 00:07:38,491
as with all good stories,

119
00:07:38,809 --> 00:07:40,877
things aren't always as they seem.

120
00:07:41,536 --> 00:07:43,253
So where were we?

121
00:07:43,421 --> 00:07:44,919
She just took the case.

122
00:07:45,044 --> 00:07:46,381
Yes, how could she not?

123
00:07:47,984 --> 00:07:49,871
What Rachel didn't know

124
00:07:50,908 --> 00:07:54,306
is that detective Olivia
once believed in love.

125
00:07:54,474 --> 00:07:56,389
Especially great love.

126
00:07:57,252 --> 00:08:00,288
And, if for no other reason,
she took this case

127
00:08:00,413 --> 00:08:03,266
to see if such a love
really existed.

128
00:08:03,859 --> 00:08:07,010
Now, this is where things
might get a bit frightening.

129
00:08:08,196 --> 00:08:10,712
I'm not sure you'd want me to go on.

130
00:08:10,837 --> 00:08:12,574
Does it have to do with Peter?

131
00:08:13,305 --> 00:08:14,275
Maybe.

132
00:08:14,723 --> 00:08:16,212
It just might.

133
00:08:18,345 --> 00:08:20,688
You see, just as Olivia

134
00:08:20,813 --> 00:08:22,751
was gathering the facts from Rachel,

135
00:08:24,374 --> 00:08:26,893
far on the other side of town,

136
00:08:27,018 --> 00:08:29,410
a young man had gone into hiding

137
00:08:29,960 --> 00:08:32,148
because he had in his possession

138
00:08:32,789 --> 00:08:35,165
a very special item.

139
00:08:35,726 --> 00:08:37,201
What kind of item?

140
00:08:37,953 --> 00:08:39,500
As it happens...

141
00:08:41,932 --> 00:08:42,930
A heart.

142
00:08:43,783 --> 00:08:47,508
But a heart unlike anything
the world had ever seen.

